    aliases: ["Yavin Eight"],
    source: "WEG40119 Galaxy Guide 2: Yavin and Bespin p.22–26",
    summary: "Yavin 8 is a cold, rocky moon of the great gas giant Yavin, lying in the same outer system as the more famous Yavin 4. The moon is characterized by snow-capped mountain ranges, broad plains, shallow inland seas, and rugged tundra. Its sole sapient inhabitants are the Melodies — a semi-aquatic species that begins life in the ocean and undergoes a dramatic metamorphosis upon reaching adulthood, abandoning the water to walk the land and losing much of their youthful grace in the process. Melody society is built around this life-transition: young Melodies (called 'streamers') live in the sea and are celebrated for their beauty and song, while adults ('walkers') dwell on the rocky shore and plains, revered for their wisdom and memory. The transformation ceremony is a spiritual and communal event. The moon is otherwise sparsely inhabited and largely unexplored by the wider galaxy. Its creature life ranges from harmless burrowers and hoppers to the enormous and predatory Ropedancer.",
    locations: "Melody sea-communities (coastal, inhabited by young streamers). Melody elder settlements (rocky shoreline and plains). Mountain ranges (snow-capped; home to Ursod predators and Ropedancers). Open plains (Herbivore Burrower and Moss-hopper habitat).",
    ofNote: "The Melody metamorphosis is a central cultural event — Jedi students from Yavin 4 sometimes travel here to witness it. Melodies in streamer form are graceful aquatic beings; as walkers they are slower but possess deep wisdom.\n\nCreatures in the Creature Lookup: Herbivore Burrower (harmless plains herbivore), Moss-hopper (venomous teeth, Sneak 5D — dangerous despite small size), Raith (eats Melody eggs, a serious threat to young Melodies), Ropedancer (12–18m long constrictor, swallows prey whole — most dangerous creature on the moon), Ursod (chameleon camouflage +2D defense, STR 5D — mountain ambush predator), Avril (flying predator), Loper (fast plains runner), Purella (web-spinning creature), Grazer (herd herbivore)."
