    source: "WEG40131 The Thrawn Trilogy Sourcebook p.123",
    summary: "Few galactic citizens have ever heard of Myrkr. Most who do are smugglers, malcontents, pirates, and other fringe members. The planet has been populated for nearly three hundred years, but in that time the Old Republic, the Jedi, and even the Empire left it strictly alone. It can be found on only a handful of astrogation charts. This isolation would be understandable if the planet was located in one of the frontiers, but it is actually not far from civilized space, near the border separating the Imperial remnants from the New Republic. Its tall trees have a high metal content that effectively blocks sensor sweeps, shielding ships and buildings hidden beneath or near their branches.",
    locations: "Karrde's Base (large central building dominated by a spacious meeting chamber with a high translucent ceiling and crisscrossing carved rafters; walls of dark brown wood with elaborate open-mesh design glowing with recessed deep blue light; furniture arranged in separate conversation circles; a huge meter-wide tree grows through the center of the room up through the ceiling, covering the building with sensor-blocking branches; abandoned after the incident with Luke Skywalker). Hyllyard City (closest thing to a true population center; small collection of makeshift structures around a large open square in a wheel pattern with narrow streets and wide spoke-like avenues; populated by settlers, free-lance smugglers, rogues, and fugitives).",
    ofNote: "Grand Admiral Thrawn was drawn to Myrkr by an obscure reference he found years ago regarding the ysalamiri — unique creatures that create Force-neutral bubbles and live within Myrkr's trees. With Karrde's cooperation, Thrawn acquired the knowledge to safely remove ysalamiri from their tree-branch perches. Later, when the Imperials returned, Karrde's organization helped Luke Skywalker and Han Solo escape by thwarting a small Imperial ground force. The trees' high metal content makes Myrkr an ideal hiding place — sensor sweeps are effectively useless under the canopy."
