    population: "28 million",
    function: "Subsistence",
    government: "Dictatorship (Joruus C'baoth)",
    techLevel: "Feudal",
    majorExports: "None",
    majorImports: "None",
    source: "WEG40131 The Thrawn Trilogy Sourcebook p.170",
    summary: "Wayland was discovered during the Old Republic's second wave of expansion. A colony ship full of humans was launched, but the world was logged improperly due to a clerical error — Wayland ceased to exist in planetary logs and astrogation charts. The colonists were cut off before they even reached their new home. The colony ship crashed on approach, but the planet had a pleasant, life-sustaining environment with two indigenous intelligent species: the Psadan and the Myneyrsh, neither of which had developed technology beyond the bow-and-arrow stage. The humans initially dominated with blasters and repulsors, but without fresh supplies their technology failed and they were forced to adopt native weapons.",
    locations: "Mount Tantiss (one of the largest peaks on the planet; hollowed out by Imperial engineers as one of the Emperor's personal storehouses; immense honeycombed cavern complex capable of supporting a full Imperial battlegroup). Upper Levels: Throne Room Complex (similar to the Death Star II throne room but smaller and more primitive; huge hologram of the galaxy tied into datavaults and HoloNet; Emperor's private turbolift keyed to retinal scan accessing all levels including the crypts). Royal Chambers (three-level personal residence of Palpatine; meeting area, information station, Force library). Emergency Shuttle Hangar (single modified Lambda-class shuttle with advanced hyperdrive near x1/2 barrier). Upper Vaults (treasure chambers up to 300m square with arched ceilings; security monitors, paralyzing nerve gas, force and repulsor fields; predominantly human artwork and historical artifacts from Core Worlds). Middle Levels: Cloning Chamber (over 20,000 Spaarti cylinders in an immense cavern over 10 stories tall; amphitheater-style balconies with central power/nutrient column; each cluster of four cylinders overlooked by a ysalamiri on a nutrient frame; produced mentally stable clones in 15-20 days). Technology Vaults (nearly 30 vaults containing plans for cloaking ship guidance, advanced stasis chambers, hive-virus bioweapons, Charon bio-tech devices, automated weapons construction). Hangar Bay (TIE fighters on roof racks with launch tubes; assault shuttles, troop transports, Skipray blastboats). Medical Bays (30 operation theaters, 200 diagnostic booths, oversized bacta tanks for up to 5 patients, two intensive care wards). Lower Levels: War Room (battle boards, hologram tanks, curved monitor screen). Command Wing (main computer core, communications center, crew pit with command platform). Main Security Section (surveillance stations, two armories, ISB office). Detention Block (with interrogation 'operating theater'). Barracks (designed for a full battlegroup; three shielded armories). City at the base of Mount Tantiss (constructed under C'baoth's influence; combines human houses, Psadan huts, and Myneyrsh castles; includes a palace incorporating all three architectural styles). Landing Field (basic starport).",
    ofNote: "When the planet was rediscovered by the Empire, the Emperor personally visited and ordered all records stricken from permanent files. Imperial engineers hollowed out Mount Tantiss to serve as a secret storehouse, its contents placed by stormtroopers and members of the Imperial court. The Emperor's Guardian — Joruus C'baoth — grew lonely after Endor and ventured out, forging the three species into a single society through dark Force manipulation. The inhabitants worshipped and feared him as almost a god or devil. Grand Admiral Thrawn found a reference to Wayland in the Obroa-skai libraries and recovered cloaking shield technology and Spaarti cloning cylinders. With C'baoth's departure, the combined society has begun to disintegrate, held together only by fear of the Guardian's return. The cloning facility may predate the Imperial installation — control components and computer systems were considerably older than other areas, as if transplanted from another facility. Han Solo and Lando Calrissian, who saw it firsthand, support this theory. Beneath the four fusion reactors (each capable of powering a Star Destroyer) lies a labyrinth — a massive maze with trac-reflective walls that prevent consistent sensor mapping. Below the labyrinth are the crypts: the Emperor's most secret treasure vault containing ancient Sith and Jedi artifacts, lightsabers, energy weapons, amulets, crystals, and mummified bodies. The architect who designed the labyrinth, Garrbo V'Droz, was personally killed by Palpatine to protect its secrets. The Heroes of Yavin exploited Mount Tantiss's major security flaw — a large air intake system midway up the exterior — to infiltrate the facility. Lando Calrissian and Chewbacca triggered a reactor overload that destroyed the mountain."
