    source: "WEG40082 Tales of the Jedi Companion pp.149-169",
    summary: "Muzara is a small Expansion Region world covered with verdant plains, wide mesas, and rough-hewn canyons. Much of its water evaporates from several large lakes, forming clouds that nourish the savannas with rain. The indigenous Muza — a tribal species evolved from nomadic ruminants — have ruled their world through sheer numbers and the complete extermination of natural predators. Their civilization is not technologically advanced, but their cultural beliefs run deep: they have no concept of property, though they revere and fear certain geographical features as sacred or unholy. A Republic colony was established only a few months ago by a Brentaal League colony cruiser. The settlers built their base atop one of the massive plateaus to oversee the agricultural operations planned for the planet. The League intends to produce foodstuffs for export to nearby settlements that are not yet self-sufficient. Immense harvester crawlers now work the savannas, tilling and sowing in spring and collecting and processing crops in fall, each machine run by several families who have purchased territory rights from the League.",
    locations: "Human colony (atop a massive plateau overlooking the agricultural zones; administrative hub for the Brentaal League operation). Harvester crawler routes (the vast savanna plains where giant agricultural machines till, sow, and harvest crops across territories staked out by farming families). Muza tribal territories (canyon, plain, and plateau regions inhabited by the indigenous Muza; certain geographic features are considered sacred or unholy by the Muza and should not be disturbed by colonists). Lake regions (several large lakes whose evaporation feeds the savanna rainfall cycle). Ruins of Kabus-Dabeh (ancient ruined site partially submerged in water; habitat of the Kabus-Dabeh Monstrosity, a large aquatic predator with maw and tentacle attacks, and the Togarn, a nocturnal predator with a spiked tail that is weakened by bright light).",
    ofNote: "4000 BBY (Tales of the Jedi era). The human colony is extremely new — only a few months old at this point. Tension between the Brentaal League's agricultural expansion and Muza territorial and sacred-site beliefs is an inherent conflict waiting to develop. The Muza's lack of a property concept makes negotiating land rights nearly impossible through conventional means. Harvester operators are essentially independent farming families who purchased territory rights from the League — they have significant personal investment at stake."
