    source: "WEG40082 Tales of the Jedi Companion",
    summary: "The Stenness Node (also called the Stenness Systems — the correct name has been debated all the way to the Senate floor) is a cluster of worlds along the border of the Inner Rim, currently outside Republic membership. The region is dominated by ore mining, with cargo ships and mining vessels constantly hauling raw materials along the Whitebeam Run ore route back and forth across the Node. One terminus of the Run is the Stenness Hyperspace Terminal, from which starships can reach other locations via jump beacon coordinates. The other terminus seems to dangle in empty space, as if the route's founders realized they had gone too far. Heavy traffic along the Run attracts pirate marauder vessels preying on ore-haulers, whose weak defensive systems make them easy targets. Since the Stenness Node is not a Republic member system, no Republic forces patrol the Run. Criminal organizations — most notably Bogga the Hutt — have moved in to offer 'protection' to miners. These advance guard units, nicknamed 'Nessies' by the locals, either escort ships for exorbitant fees or patrol the Run in predictable patterns. Some miners suspect collusion between the raiders and the protectors but dare not speak out. Ore-haulers have been known to pay mercenaries 500–1,000 credits per trip for independent protection.",
    locations: "Stenness Hyperspace Terminal (major trade hub and jump beacon terminus at one end of the Whitebeam Run; see Stenness - Hyperspace Terminal). Whitebeam Run (the primary ore route traversing the Stenness Node; heavily trafficked by mining vessels and preyed upon by pirates; Nessie advance guard patrols run in predictable patterns). Worlds of the Node: Ambria, Onderon, Taboon (with Vo Dasha moon) — all within the Stenness Node's borders.",
    ofNote: "4000 BBY (Tales of the Jedi era). The Stenness Node is not a Republic member system — no Republic military or law enforcement operates here. Bogga the Hutt (4000 BBY) is the dominant criminal power. Ore-hauler captains seeking mercenary protection typically pay 500–1,000 credits per trip along the Whitebeam Run."
